## Sextant Engineering Protocol

This project uses [Sextant](https://github.com/zzf2333/Sextant) — an engineering mindset framework
that constrains AI coding behavior to a clearer, more verifiable path.

### Starting a task

For most tasks, start with:

```
/sextant "what you want to build"
```

This runs Spec, Plan, Build, Verify, and Record — pausing only at meaningful decision
points. No manual stage-driving required for standard L0/L1 work.

### Explicit stage commands

For advanced control, debugging, or L2 tasks requiring step-by-step review:

- `/sextant-spec` — define scope, constraints, and acceptance criteria
- `/sextant-plan` — produce the minimal implementation approach
- `/sextant-build` — implement strictly within the approved plan
- `/sextant-verify` — run tools + adversarial review
- `/sextant-record` — write back knowledge and close the task
- `/sextant-status` — see where you are and what to do next

### Task classification

Tasks are automatically classified as L0 / L1 / L2. Use `--force-l0/l1/l2` to override.
L2 tasks (data model, auth, payment, sync) require reviewer approval at all stages.
For L2 tasks, prefer explicit stage commands over `/sextant` for step-by-step control.

### Knowledge files

This project maintains four Sextant knowledge files. Read them at task start:

- `SEXTANT.md` — current tech stack, verify commands, explicit non-goals
- `modules/*/EVOLUTION.md` — module-level design history
- `PROJECT_EVOLUTION_LOG.md` — project-level architectural decisions
- `hook-registry.json` — mechanically enforceable rules

Do not start a task without reading `SEXTANT.md` first.

### Reviewer rule

The reviewer role has one non-negotiable constraint: every review output must contain a
`deletion_proposals` field. If nothing qualifies for deletion, write `none` explicitly.

### Recovery

If you lose track of where a task is, run `/sextant-status` to get a full state report
and the recommended next action.
